        "content": "<p>It's not a coincidence.    I think it's very important.  But I think it's still somewhat mysterious.    I don't think anyone has figured out a general framework in which the common features of FHilb and Cat both emerge as special cases.    One thing I did was invent \"2-Hilbert spaces\", which are like Hilbert spaces, but categories instead of sets:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>John Baez, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/q-alg/9609018\">Higher-dimensional algebra II: 2-Hilbert spaces</a>, Adv. Math. 127 (1997), 125-189. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>The hom of a 2-Hilbert space plays the role of its inner product.   There are lots of nice examples of 2-Hilbert spaces in physics and mathematics, like categories of unitary representations of groups.</p>",
        "id": 249155867,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628709430
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Bruce Bartlett has done some <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/0807.1329\">nice work on 2-Hilbert spaces</a>, improving my definition a bit.</p>",
        "id": 249156177,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628709585
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks! exactly what I am looking for it seems</p>",
        "id": 249156984,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Van Muylder",
        "timestamp": 1628709980
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>there is this table in the representation theory book from Etingof et al: <a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ozhunQbNg2i70oQcxfL8EAsz/unknown.png\">unknown.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ozhunQbNg2i70oQcxfL8EAsz/unknown.png\" title=\"unknown.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/ozhunQbNg2i70oQcxfL8EAsz/unknown.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 249198922,
        "sender_full_name": "Naso",
        "timestamp": 1628745715
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The closest thing I know of to a general framework that includes both FHilb and Cat is the Chu construction.</p>",
        "id": 249231257,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1628773339
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah!  Chu!</p>",
        "id": 249246890,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628780710
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm finally interested in the Chu construction.  Nobody ever said that sentence to me before.   Oh - but why do you say \"the closest thing\"?  Does it not quite capture those two examples?</p>",
        "id": 249247060,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628780783
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, it depends on exactly what aspects of those two examples you want to capture, and what you mean by \"capture\".  As I sketched in <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/286343/49\">this MO answer</a>, the main point is that the two Chu-constructions Chu(Vect,k) and Chu(Cat,Set) contain as full subcategories the category of Hilbert spaces and adjoint pairs of transformations, and the category of categories and adjoint pars of functors, respectively.  This doesn't directly address the Yoneda-type question of the OP, though.</p>",
        "id": 249273658,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1628792803
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/inner.20products.20work.20a.20bit.20like.20homs/near/249273658\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Well, it depends on exactly what aspects of those two examples you want to capture, and what you mean by \"capture\".  As I sketched in <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/286343/49\">this MO answer</a>, the main point is that the two Chu-constructions Chu(Vect,k) and Chu(Cat,Set) contain as full subcategories the category of Hilbert spaces and adjoint pairs of transformations, and the category of categories and adjoint pars of functors, respectively.  This doesn't directly address the Yoneda-type question of the OP, though.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>as evidence of [PS nietzsche's eternally returning idea of] eternal return, i copy a conversation (started by jdolan) from the categories mailing list from 5/9/2001:</p>\n<p>Peter Freyd wrote:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A good question. I have no answer, only a similar (and ancient)<br>\nquestion: is there a setting in which adjoint operators on Hilbert<br>\nspaces can be seen to be examples of adjoint functors between<br>\ncategories?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>probably not, but the they seem to be instances of the same general<br>\nstructure. (it is simple, pretty old, and i am sure many have noticed it,<br>\nbut since no one mentioned it, here it goes.)</p>\n<p>let U :   Cat     ---&gt; CAT be the embedding of small categories in all,<br>\nand<br>\nlet Y: Cat^op ---&gt; CAT map each small category A to the presheaves<br>\nPsh(A).</p>\n<p>now look at the (pseudo)comma category U/Y. each category A is<br>\nrepresented in it by the yoneda embedding A--&gt;Psh(A). the morphisms<br>\nbetween A--&gt;Psh(A) and B --&gt; Psh(B) are exactly the pairs of adjoint<br>\nfunctors between A and B.</p>\n<p>on the other hand, let I: Vec---&gt; Vec be the identity functor,<br>\nand let * : Vec^op ---&gt; Vec take a vector space V to its dual V*.</p>\n<p>look at the comma category I/*. each hilbert space V is represented in it<br>\nby the obvious linear map  V--&gt;V<em>. the morphisms between V--&gt;V</em> and<br>\nW--&gt;W* are exactly the adjoint pairs of operators between V and W.</p>\n<p>playing around a bit, these two comma categories can be thought of as<br>\nChu(CAT,Set) and Chu(Vec,R) respectively. so both sorts of adjunctions<br>\nare the instances of the chu morphisms. they are the chu morphisms on the<br>\n\"representation\" objects, in the form X --&gt; R^X, where R is the dualizing<br>\nobject.</p>\n<p>-- dusko</p>\n<p>PS infact, one could start from Chu(SET,Set), and define categories as<br>\nthe profunctors A--&gt;Set^A which form a monoid with respect to the<br>\nprofunctor composition. you'd get only the object part of the adjoint<br>\nfunctors as the morphisms of this chu, but the arrow part follows from<br>\nthe adjunction (i think).</p>\n<p>now can we characterize hilbert spaces in a similar way within<br>\nChu(Vec,R)? this seems to be a completely different kind of question. in<br>\nparticular, it is possible to define \"profunctors\" with respect to R or<br>\nC, like we did with respect to Set, and we can compose them, but hilbert<br>\nspaces do not seem to be monoids with respect to this composition, at<br>\nleast the way it occurs to me. if there is no such composition that they<br>\nare, then hilbert spaces are like R-enriched graphs, rather than<br>\ncategories.</p>",
        "id": 250213205,
        "sender_full_name": "dusko",
        "timestamp": 1629546375
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, but in the meantime i know that adjoint operators over <em>real</em> hilbert spaces with bases <em>are</em> the kan extensions of their matrix form as an enriched profunctor over the category of reals. so my first \"probably not\" to freyd's question was wrong.</p>",
        "id": 250213411,
        "sender_full_name": "dusko",
        "timestamp": 1629546696
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for finding that.  I certainly didn't mean to claim any originality for the observation!</p>",
